I stand in awe amongst some of the collection of 7000+ scotch bottles, while holding our tasting glasses, at the Scotch Whiskey Experience. www.scotchwhiskyexperience.co.uk/

As part of the Gold Tour at the Scotch Whiskey Experience we received our tasting trays consisting of four Single Malts from the four main scotch producing regions of Scotland (Lowland, Highland, Speyside and Islay) with tasting notes.

The bottle with the white piece of paper beside it is supposedly the oldest bottle of Scotch in the collection, dating back to around the late 1800s, if I remember correctly.

What I went on just to get some Scotch and a free glass turned out to be a really fantastic tour of how it's actually made. 
If you stop by Edinburgh, I highly recommend it.

According to our tour guide, this is the largest collection of Scotch in the entire world.
After the tour was over with, we watched our professors get utterly smashed at the bar, and had to fill them up with some dinner to soak up the liquor before heading back to the hostel.
All in all, a great way to spend a rainy day in Edinburgh.

description._content: in a world of its own..... The World's End on the Royal Mile! Back in the 16th century Edinburgh was a walled city. The gates to the city were situated outside the pub, and the brass cobbles in the road represent their exact location. As far as the people of Edinburgh were concerned, the world outside these gates was no longer theirs: hence the name, The World's End. SAMSUNG CSC

in a world of its own..... The World's End on the Royal Mile! Back in the 16th century Edinburgh was a walled city. The gates to the city were situated outside the pub, and the brass cobbles in the road represent their exact location. As far as the people of Edinburgh were concerned, the world outside these gates was no longer theirs: hence the name, The World's End.
Along Edinburgh's Royal Mile, there are a number of alleyways (or as they call them there Close).  Each one is a mystery and can offer a delightful view, a path to a cafe, or perhaps danger?

This former church on the Royal Mile in Edinburgh Scotland is now referred to as the Hub.  

The gothic spires are still doing what they were designed to do... to make your eyes glance upward to the heavens.

The walk from Hollyrood Castle to Edinburgh Castle is about a mile... uphill.  Along the way you pass several pubs, whiskey shops, and other quaint little stores.

The buildings are not actually tilted... I made the street horizontal when I framed the shot.
